---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-portugal', text: 'Leaving Portuguese Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'eu-coordination', text: 'EU & CPLP Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-portugal', text: 'Returning to Portugal', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Allianz Care Review', href: '/providers/allianz-care' },
  { title: 'Portugal D7 Visa Insurance', href: '/compare/best-insurance-for-portugal-d7-visa' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Brazilian Expat Insurance', href: '/best/brazilian-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'portugueseSupport', header: 'Portuguese' },
  { key: 'euNetwork', header: 'EU Network' },
  { key: 'portugalCoverage', header: 'Portugal Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', portugueseSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Strong', portugalCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€170/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', portugueseSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Excellent', portugalCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Multicare', portugueseSupport: 'Full (Portuguese)', euNetwork: 'Good', portugalCoverage: 'Included', price: '€120/mo' },
  { provider: 'Médis', portugueseSupport: 'Full (Portuguese)', euNetwork: 'Good', portugalCoverage: 'Included', price: '€130/mo' },
  { provider: 'April International', portugueseSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Strong', portugalCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€150/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Portuguese Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Portuguese expats. Find coverage for France, Switzerland, Luxembourg, UK, and other popular destinations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Portuguese Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Portuguese expats are found across Europe, Brazil, and beyond. Here's how to stay covered while preserving your SNS rights at home."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/portuguese-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Portuguese expats have strong communities in France, Switzerland, Luxembourg, UK, and Brazil. Your insurance needs depend on whether you're staying in the EU (where coordination applies) or going further. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Portuguese expats. Strong networks worldwide, Portuguese support available, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Excellent for EU destinations. Strong European networks, Portuguese support, competitive pricing.</li>
    <li><strong>Multicare:</strong> Portuguese insurer with international options. Familiar brand, full Portuguese service, includes Portugal coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Médis:</strong> Another major Portuguese option. Good EU coverage, Portuguese service, includes home country coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>April International:</strong> French insurer with good Portuguese support. Strong in francophone countries where many Portuguese work.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="EU Coordination"
    description="Working in another EU country typically enrolls you in that country's healthcare system. You may not need separate international insurance—but private coverage improves access and covers visits to Portugal."
    buttonText="Compare Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-portugal">Leaving Portuguese Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Portugal's SNS (Serviço Nacional de Saúde) provides universal healthcare to residents. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>SNS Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    SNS coverage is based on residence in Portugal. When you establish residence elsewhere, your entitlement to routine SNS care ends. Your Cartão de Utente remains valid for visits, but you're considered a temporary user rather than a resident.
  </p>

  <h3>CESD (Cartão Europeu de Seguro de Doença)</h3>
  <p>
    Your Portuguese EHIC covers emergency care in other EU countries while you're Portuguese-insured. Once you register in another EU country's system, you should get that country's EHIC instead.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Portuguese Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Portuguese private insurers (Multicare, Médis, Fidelidade) typically offer limited international coverage—usually 30-90 days of emergency treatment. For long-term stays abroad, you need dedicated international coverage or an international product from your Portuguese insurer.
  </p>

  <h2 id="eu-coordination">EU & CPLP Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Portugal has specific relationships that affect expat healthcare:
  </p>

  <h3>EU Social Security Coordination</h3>
  <p>
    Working in another EU country enrolls you in that country's social security system. Your contributions there count toward Portuguese pension rights. The S1 form transfers your healthcare entitlement if you're receiving Portuguese benefits abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>Switzerland</h3>
  <p>
    Switzerland has bilateral agreements with the EU. Portuguese workers in Switzerland are covered by Swiss social security and healthcare. The agreements coordinate pension rights between countries.
  </p>

  <h3>CPLP Countries (Brazil, Angola, Mozambique, etc.)</h3>
  <p>
    Portugal has healthcare agreements with some CPLP (Portuguese-speaking) countries, but coverage is typically limited to emergency care. For comprehensive coverage in Brazil or African Portuguese-speaking countries, you need international insurance.
  </p>

  <h3>Luxembourg</h3>
  <p>
    Large Portuguese community with well-established services. Luxembourg's healthcare system covers employed residents. Many Portuguese maintain private insurance for access to Portuguese-speaking doctors and coverage during Portugal visits.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Pension Considerations</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Contact Segurança Social before leaving Portugal to understand how your pension contributions will be affected. EU coordination ensures contributions abroad count, but documentation requirements vary.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage ideal for Portuguese expats anywhere in the world. Strong networks throughout Europe, Americas, and beyond. Portuguese-language support is available.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited. Direct billing at major hospitals worldwide. Portugal coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Portuguese expats who want reliable global coverage with Portuguese support.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers excellent European coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks in France, Switzerland, and Luxembourg—major Portuguese expat destinations. Portuguese support is available through their European operations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Portuguese expats in EU countries who want comprehensive private coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Multicare</h3>
  <p>
    Multicare is one of Portugal's largest health insurers, offering international products for Portuguese expats. Full Portuguese service, familiar claims process, and Portugal coverage included automatically.
  </p>

  <p>
    International networks are adequate, though not as extensive as Cigna or Allianz. Good option for those preferring a Portuguese provider.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Portuguese expats who want familiar Portuguese service and seamless home coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Médis</h3>
  <p>
    Médis (part of Ageas Group) offers similar international coverage to Multicare. Full Portuguese service, good EU coverage, Portugal included. Competitive pricing for Portuguese expats.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Portuguese expats seeking good value from a familiar Portuguese brand.
  </p>

  <h3>April International</h3>
  <p>
    April International is a French insurer with strong Portuguese support—useful for the large Portuguese community in France. Good coverage throughout francophone countries and the EU.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Portuguese expats in France or other French-speaking countries.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Portuguese and International Options"
    description="Portuguese insurers offer familiarity; international insurers have broader networks. Compare both based on your destination."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-portugal">Returning to Portugal</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Portuguese healthcare is straightforward for Portuguese citizens:
  </p>

  <h3>Re-registering Residence</h3>
  <p>
    Update your morada fiscal (tax address) with Finanças and register at your local Centro de Saúde. This re-establishes your SNS entitlement.
  </p>

  <h3>SNS Access</h3>
  <p>
    Once registered, you can access SNS services including your Centro de Saúde for primary care. Request or update your Cartão de Utente. Choose a médico de família (family doctor) in your area.
  </p>

  <h3>EU Coordination on Return</h3>
  <p>
    Bring documentation of social security contributions from your EU country of residence. Forms S1/E104 help ensure continuous recognition of your contribution history.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Period</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active until SNS registration is complete. The process is usually quick for Portuguese citizens, but having overlap prevents gaps.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I use SNS during visits to Portugal?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Your Cartão de Utente remains valid, but you're treated as a temporary user. International insurance with Portugal coverage ensures full access without complications.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Do I need insurance in France if I'm employed there?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">French employment enrolls you in Sécurité Sociale. Private insurance is optional but provides faster access and covers Portugal visits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage in Brazil?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Despite language ties, healthcare agreements are limited. You need international insurance for comprehensive coverage in Brazil.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Multicare or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Multicare offers Portuguese familiarity and includes Portugal. Cigna has stronger global networks. Choose based on destination and preference.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Portuguese doctors abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">In France, Switzerland, Luxembourg, and UK, you can find Portuguese-speaking doctors. Your insurer can help locate providers.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about my Portuguese pension?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">EU coordination protects your pension rights. Contributions in other EU countries count toward your Portuguese pension.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Portuguese expats in the EU often have local healthcare access, but private insurance improves quality and covers home visits. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for comprehensive worldwide coverage. <strong>Allianz Care</strong> offers excellent value for EU destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Multicare</strong> and <strong>Médis</strong> are ideal for those wanting Portuguese service and included Portugal coverage. <strong>April International</strong> suits expats in francophone countries.
  </p>

  <p>
    Contact Segurança Social before leaving to understand pension coordination, and keep documentation of contributions from abroad for your eventual return.
  </p>

</PageShell>
